The Seven Years War had major global and geopolitcal consequences. But in North America, The British Empire had emerged not only victories, but a number of unresolved issues. These issues would eventually lead to the American Revolution.

8. The Sugar Act
In 1764, Parliament enacted the Sugar Act. This act greatly increased duties on colonial goods being brought into the British Empire. In particular, the act increased taxes on sugar import. But the act also restricted colonial trade to avoid "a smuggling trade".
9. Proclamations
The Proclamations were a series of British acts that granted Native Americans land on the Appalachian Frontier (lands west of the Applalachian Mountains that ran from Maine to Georgia).
This act restricted colonial activity in the west and gave Native Americans greater access to the land.
10. Colonies
The British Empire's New American colonies included:
The British colonies in British North America also included the Thirteen Colonies that were independent states on January 2, 1776. The colonies were created as part of the New World British empire. The colonies were the original 13 colonies.
11. Intolerable Acts
The Intolerable Acts were the final measures enacted by the British Empire in response to the Boston Tea Party. The acts included shutting down the port of Boston, quartering soldiers with "diseases transmissible to the inhabitants", and closing the Massachusetts Assembly of the colony assembly.

14. Quartering Act
The Quartering Act was part of the series of British imperial acts called the Intolerable Acts. It required Massachusetts to house British soldiers in private homes, a major cause of the Boston Massacre, which was also a catalyst of the American Revolutionary War.
15. Taxation without Representation
The Founding Fathers of the American Revolution often asserted that the American colonists were paying taxes but they had no representation in Parliament (a major cause of the Stamp Act in 1765) and were not afforded the same basic rights as British subjects, the most basic of which was the right to be tried without being in London, England. They also said that the colonists were getting the "worst end of the deal."
